SENATE JOINT RESOLUTION 883
By Massey
A RESOLUTION to honor the memory of Charles R. Harr of
Knoxville.
WHEREAS, the members of this General Assembly were greatly saddened to learn of
the passing of Charles R. Harr of Knoxville; and
WHEREAS, Mr. Harr was an exemplary public servant and consummate professional
who worked assiduously to improve the quality of life for his fellow citizens in numerous
capacities; and
WHEREAS, Charlie Harr graduated from Wichita Falls High School, West Texas State
University with a Bachelor of Science degree, and Troy State University with a Master of
Science degree; and
WHEREAS, a proud veteran, Mr. Harr served in the United States Air Force, flying
fighter aircraft for twenty-six years, and retired at the rank of colonel; he was a veteran of
Vietnam and Desert Storm and received numerous awards during combat, including the Legion
of Merit, three Distinguished Flying Crosses, a Bronze Star, twelve Air Medals, a Vietnam Cross
of Gallantry, and the Kuwait Liberation Medal; and
WHEREAS, he was a member of several organizations, including the Super Saber
Society, Distinguished Flying Cross Society, and the Air Force Association; and
WHEREAS, upon retirement from the Air Force, Charlie Harr became a certified financial
planner at Patriot Investment Management, where he cared for his clients until his death; and
WHEREAS, an active leader in his community, Mr. Harr served as a Metropolitan
Knoxville Airport Authority Commissioner, Dogwood Arts Festival Board Treasurer, Financial
Planning Association of East Tennessee President, East Tennessee Veterans Memorial
Association Board Treasurer, United Way of Greater Knoxville Allocations, Rotary Club of
SJR0883
014293
- 1 -

Knoxville Secretary and Scholarship Committee Chair, and as a member of the HonorAir
Knoxville Board and Flight Leadership Team; and
WHEREAS, Charlie Harr's innate ability as a community leader was characterized by his
integrity, honesty, and loyalty; and
WHEREAS, Mr. Harr was an active member of Middlebrook Pike United Methodist
Church, where he served as Church Leadership Council Chair, Finance Committee Chair, and
Endowment Committee Chair; in addition to serving his church, he also served the Methodist
denomination through the Holston Conference as Chair of the Board of Pensions, Chair of the
Investment Committee of the Holston Conference Foundation, and as a Holston Home for
Children Foundation Board member; and
WHEREAS, Charlie Harr was deeply devoted to family, and he always endeavored to
remain true to family values of the highest order; and
WHEREAS, he will be sadly missed but fondly remembered by his beloved wife of fifty-
eight years, Lynne Harr; his brother-in-law, Chuck Masterson; and many nieces, nephews, and
cousins; and
WHEREAS, Mr. Harr was preceded in death by his parents, Russell and Charlotte Harr;
his sister, Ruth Masterson; his parents-in-law, Jack and Peggy Parkins; his brother-in-law, Mark
Parkins; and his nephew, Matthew Parkins; and
WHEREAS, Charlie Harr leaves behind an indelible legacy of integrity and probity in
public life, compassion and loyalty in private life, and diligence and dedication in all his chosen
endeavors; and
WHEREAS, it is fitting that the members of this General Assembly should pause to
remember the bountiful life of this exceptional public servant and human being; now, therefore,
BE IT RESOLVED BY THE SENATE OF THE ONE HUNDRED FOURTEENTH
GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE HOUSE OF
- 2 - 014293

REPRESENTATIVES CONCURRING, that we honor the memory of Charles R. Harr, reflecting
fondly upon his impeccable character and his stalwart commitment to living the examined life
with courage and conviction.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that we express our sympathy and offer our condolences
to the family and friends of Mr. Harr.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy and upon proper request made to
the appropriate clerk, the language appearing immediately following the State seal appear
without House or Senate designation.
